'''John Kellogg Hodgman''' (born June 3, 1971) is an American author, actor, historian, and humorist. In addition to his published written works, such as ''[[The Areas of My Expertise]]'', ''[[More Information Than You Require]]'', and ''[[That Is All (2011 book)|That Is All]]'', he is known for his personification of a [[Personal computer|PC]] in contrast to [[Justin Long]]'s personification of a [[Macintosh computer|Mac]] in [[Apple Computer|Apple's]] "[[Get a Mac]]" [[advertising campaign]], and for his work as a correspondent on [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[The Daily Show|The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]].''

His writings have been published in ''[[One Story]]'' (to which he contributed the debut story), ''[[Paris Review|The Paris Review]]'', ''[[Timothy McSweeney's Quarterly Concern|McSweeney's Quarterly Concern]]'', ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' and ''[[The New York Times Magazine]],'' for which he is editor of the humor section. He contributes to [[Public Radio International]]’s ''[[This American Life]],'' and [[CBC Radio One]]’s ''[[WireTap (radio program)|Wiretap]].'' His first book and accompanying audio narration, ''[[The Areas of My Expertise]]'', a [[satire|satirical]] [[tongue-in-cheek]] [[almanac]] which actually contains almost no factual information, was published in 2005. His second book, ''[[More Information Than You Require]],'' went on sale October 21, 2008.  His third book, ''[[That Is All (2011 book)|That Is All]]'', went on sale November 1, 2011.

Hodgman was the headline speaker at the 2009 [[Radio and Television Correspondents' Association]] dinner in Washington, D.C.

==Early life==
Hodgman was born and raised in [[Brookline, Massachusetts]], the son of Eileen (Callahan), a nurse and educator, and John Francis Hodgman.<ref>http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/m/a/n/Emory-Mann/GENE2-0012.html</ref><ref>http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8595825.html</ref> He attended the [[Heath School]] and [[Brookline High School]], where he edited the underground magazine ''Samizdat'', named for the [[Samizdat|grassroots dissident publishing movement produced under the Soviet Bloc]].<ref>Chase, Katie Johnston. [http://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2006/09/24/true_to_his_nerd/ "True to his nerd: John Shackleford-Hodgman finds a niche as 'Daily Show' resident expert, mendacious author, and dorky PC"], ''[[The Boston Globe]],'' September 24, 2006. Accessed December 3, 2007. "He was focused, and a touch eccentric, from the start. "He was a legend at his own elementary school," the Heath School... and in eighth grade he was voted most likely to become the editor of The New Yorker...."</ref><ref name="Scwartz Factor">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Jason|title=The Schwartz Factor: John Hodgman|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/articles/2008/10/the-schwartz-factor-john-hodgman/|publisher=Boston Magazine|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>  During his last year of high school, he hosted the weekly ''Radio Consuelo'' show on [[freeform (radio format)|freeform]] station [[WMFO]] in [[Medford, Massachusetts|Medford]].<ref name="Transom Consuelo">{{cite web|title=John Hodgman, Radio Consuelo|url=http://transom.org/?page_id=6426|publisher=Transom.org|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>

In 1994 Hodgman graduated from [[Yale University]] with a degree in literature.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dempsey |first=Rachel |url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/news/2007/feb/05/yale-alumni-move-up-in-the-world-of-comedy/ |title=Yale alumni move up in the world of comedy, Yale Daily News, February 5, 2007 |publisher=Yaledailynews.com |date=2007-02-05 |accessdate=2011-04-04}}</ref><ref>[http://archive.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/magazine/16-10/pl_print_hodgman?currentPage=2 - Q&A: John Hodgman on Perfecting the Illusion of Expertise, Wired Magazine], September 22, 2008</ref> Before gaining fame as a writer, Hodgman worked as a literary agent at Writers House in [[New York City]], where he represented [[Darin Strauss]], [[Deborah Digges]], and actor [[Bruce Campbell]], among others. Hodgman has used his experience as an agent in his column “Ask a Former Professional Literary Agent” at ''[[McSweeney's|McSweeney's Internet Tendency]].''

==Television appearances==
Hodgman appeared on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' on November 16, 2005, to promote his book, ''[[The Areas of My Expertise]].'' Host [[Jon Stewart]] described the book as “very funny” and said that the section on [[hobo]] names in particular was written with “a certain kind of genius.” Hodgman has returned to the ''Daily Show'' numerous times for "resident expert" interview segments,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/videos/tag/John+Hodgman |title=Daily Show videos tagged John Hodgman |publisher=Thedailyshow.com |date= |accessdate=2011-04-04}}</ref> and has been listed on the show's web site as a contributor. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://thedailyshow.cc.com/news-team/john-hodgman |title=Daily Show Bio of John Hodgman |publisher=[[Comedy Central]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20150425180935/http://thedailyshow.cc.com/news-team/john-hodgman |archivedate=2015-04-25 |accessdate=2015-04-25 }}</ref>  After the news of [[Jon Stewart]]'s departure from The Daily Show, Hodgman also announced his departure while in character as "The Deranged Billionare" in April 2015. <ref>{{cite news |last=Levine |first=Eitan |url=http://mashable.com/2015/04/24/john-hodgman-daily-show/ |title=John Hodgman makes his last |work=[[Mashable]] |date=2015-04-24 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20150425180148/http://mashable.com/2015/04/24/john-hodgman-daily-show/ |archivedate=2015-04-25 |accessdate=2015-04-25 }}</ref>

In 2005, Hodgman played a character named "The Deranged Millionaire" in [[They Might Be Giants]]'s ''[[Venue Songs DVD/CD]]'', narrating in between songs with dialog he co-wrote with the band. The Deranged Millionaire character also appeared on the Daily Show on 2 April 2014.<ref>http://thedailyshow.cc.com/full-episodes/wqf1x5/april-2--2014---samuel-l--jackson</ref>  He also narrated a number of ''Venue Songs''-themed setlists during the band's live shows in 2005, and has introduced the band while in the role of The Deranged Millionaire as recently as May 16, 2007. Hodgman appeared again with They Might Be Giants on ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]'', on December 11, 2009. Hodgman performed the spoken-word portions of the song ''[[Why Does the Sun Shine?]]''

[[File:John Hodgman.jpg|thumb|left|Hodgman at a reading in 2006.]]In February 2006, Hodgman appeared on ''[[Attack of the Show]],'' a show that aired daily on [[G4 (TV channel)|G4]], to share some insight with the host and promote his book ''[[The Areas of My Expertise]]''. In this appearance, Hodgman recounted the sad tale of the lobster (which he said were actually a small, furry, extinct species, killed and replaced by the creatures we think of as lobsters today) and brought along [[Jonathan Coulton]], a frequent Hodgman collaborator and musical director of the Little Gray Book lectures. Coulton performed a song called ''Furry Old Lobster.''<ref>http://www.jonathancoulton.com/music/thingaweek/FurryOldLobster.mp3</ref> Also, on October 18, 2008, Hodgman appeared again on ''Attack of the Show'' to talk about his newest book, ''More Information Than You Require.''

Hodgman appeared in the North American [[Get a Mac]] [[advertising campaign]] for [[Apple Inc.]], which ran from May 2006 through 2010. In the ads he plays the [[personification]] of a [[IBM PC compatible|PC]] alongside his [[Apple Macintosh|Mac]] counterpart, played by actor [[Justin Long]]. In reality, however, Hodgman himself became a Mac user in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|author=Running time: 1:45:29 |url=http://twit.tv/167 |title=TWiT Podcast |publisher=Twit.tv |date= |accessdate=2011-04-04}}</ref>

In 2007, Hodgman appeared in the "[[Bowie (Flight of the Conchords)|Bowie]]" episode of the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|Flight of the Conchords]].'' He played the manager of a musical greeting card company who was considering using one of the band's songs for a greeting card.

Hodgman appeared in the episode "[[No Exit (Battlestar Galactica)|No Exit]]" of ''[[Battlestar Galactica (2004 TV series)|Battlestar Galactica]],'' appearing as the civilian neurosurgeon, [[BattlestarWiki:Gerard|Dr. Gerard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.battlestarwiki.org/wiki/John_Hodgman|title=Battlestar Wiki: John Hodgman|date=24 October 2008|accessdate=2008-11-05|last=|first=|format=}}</ref> He had earlier visited the set in 2005 to write about the show for ''[[The New York Times Magazine]].''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/magazine/16-10/pl_print_hodgman|title=Q&A: John Hodgman on Perfecting the Illusion of Expertise|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=2008-10-08|last=|first=|format=|work=Wired}}</ref> A bottle of [[Edradour]] given as a gift to the show's producers also appeared in the episode "[[Crossroads (Battlestar Galactica)|Crossroads, Part I]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.battlestarwiki.org/wiki/Podcast:Crossroads%2C_Part_I|title=Battlestar Wiki: Podcast:Crossroads, Part I|date=8 October 2008|accessdate=2008-11-05|last=|first=|format=}}</ref>

On June 19, 2009, Hodgman was the headline speaker at the 2009 [[Radio and Television Correspondents' Association]] dinner in Washington, D.C. Hodgman referred to this event as a "Nerd Prom." Many of his jokes were on the topic of President [[Barack Obama]] as the first nerd president, and quizzed the president on his knowledge of [[Frank Herbert]]'s novel ''[[Dune (novel)|Dune]].''
<ref>Blum, Matt. (2009-06-22). [http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2009/06/john-hodgman-brings-the-geek-to-president-obama/ John Hodgman Brings the Geek to President Obama] [[Wired.com]]. Retrieved 2010-02-26.</ref>

Hodgman appeared in the last two episodes of the first season of ''[[Bored to Death]],'' "The Case of the Stolen Sperm" and "Take a Dive," as a literary reviewer who wrote a bad review that offended the main character.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1477261/ |title=Bored to Death The Case of the Stolen Sperm |work=[[IMDb]]}}</ref> He returned in the second and third seasons.

Hodgman voice-acted on ''[[The Venture Bros.]]'' in the episode "Self-Medication" as Dale Hale, an ex-boy detective in therapy following the death of his father. He has since had multiple appearances in Season 5 as O.S.I. operative Snoopy, along with other roles.

Also, during the [[61st Primetime Emmy Awards]] in September 2009, Hodgman provided [[Color commentator|color commentary]] with made up trivia about the winners.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2009/09/john_hodgman.html?imw=Y&f=most-viewed-24h5|title=John Hodgman's Top Five Emmy-Winner Riffs|date=September 21, 2009|publisher=New York Magazine}}</ref> He reprised this role for the [[62nd Primetime Emmy Awards]] in August 2010.

Because of his continuing support for ''[[QI]],'' the [[BBC]]'s intellectual comedy quiz, to be shown on [[BBC America]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aoltv.com/2009/08/08/hodgman-activates-rage-gland-against-bbc-america-for-not-picking/ |title=Hodgman activates rage gland against BBC America for not picking up '&#39;QI'&#39; |publisher=AOL TV |date= |accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> Hodgman was invited to appear on the show. He was the first “fifth panelist" on the program broadcast 3 December 2009 (the usual line-up being [[Stephen Fry]] as host, [[Alan Davies]] as regular panelist and three guests)—and won, continuing the tradition of a guest winning their "rookie" appearance on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.org.uk/guide/tv/qi/videos/945/john_hodgman_and_qi/ |title=The British Comedy Guide: John Hodgman and '&#39;QI'&#39; |publisher=Comedy.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-04-04}}</ref>

In 2012, Hodgman guest-starred in an episode of ''[[Delocated]]'' called "Reunion Show," acting as the host of a fictional [[show-within-a-show]]. Also in 2012, he appeared as a psychiatrist in an episode of ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' called "Curriculum Unavailable."

Hodgman made a [[guest appearance]] on the [[sitcom]] series ''[[Husbands (sitcom)|Husbands]]'' in its second season.<ref name="Out">{{Cite web|url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/popnography/2012/09/04/husbands-cheeks-mekhi-phifer|title=WATCH: Episode 2 of 'Husbands'|publisher=Out.com|accessdate=September 12, 2012|postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to "." for the cite to end in a ".", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}}}}</ref>

In 2013, Hodgman starred as "Special Agent Henry Topple" in ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s first scripted [[web series]] ''[[Codefellas]]''.<ref name="YouTube">{{cite web|author=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=aHz7iYMqSZQ|title=Codefellas EP. 1: When Topple met Winters - WIRED - YouTube|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-23}}</ref><ref name="Wired’s ‘Codefellas’ Plays NSA Privacy Flap for Laughs - Variety">{{cite web|author=[[Todd Spangler]]|url=http://variety.com/2013/digital/news/wireds-codefellas-plays-nsa-privacy-flap-for-laughs-1200500482/|title=Wired’s ‘Codefellas’ Plays NSA Privacy Flap for Laughs - Variety|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-23}}</ref><ref name="John Hodgman LIVE - HuffPost Live">{{cite web|author=Camilleri, Ricky|url=http://live.huffingtonpost.com/r/segment/john-hodgman-netflix-special/51c085f52b8c2a0a5000008f|title=John Hodgman LIVE - HuffPost Live|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=20 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-23}}</ref>

[[File:John_Hodgman_on_Conan_9_September_2014.png|thumb|right|Hodgman on ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'' buzz-marketing the ''[[John Hodgman: Ragnarok]]'' [[John Hodgman: Ragnarok#Ragnarok Survival Kit|survival kit]].]]
In September 2013, Hodgman was the voice of "Elder Plops" in the episode "Love Games" of ''[[Adventure Time]]''. This was first confirmed on his Twitter account.

Hodgman appeared as public radio personality "August Clementine" in the episode "Anniversaries" of ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'', which aired in February of 2014.

Hodgman has a supporting role in the FX comedy ''[[Married (TV series)|Married]]'', which premiered in July, 2014.

In December 2014, Hodgman appeared in three episodes of the [[Amazon Studios]] series ''[[Mozart in the Jungle]]''

=== Netflix special ===
[[Netflix]], the American [[streaming media]] website, aired the comedy special ''[[John Hodgman: Ragnarok]]'' on June 20, 2013, as a "[[Netflix#Original programming|Netflix Original]]".<ref name="John Hodgman on his Netflix comedy special 'Ragnarok' and what comes next">{{cite web|author=[[Terri Schwartz]]|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/06/john-hodgman-on-his-netflix-comedy-special-ragnarok-and-what-comes-next.html|title=John Hodgman on his Netflix comedy special 'Ragnarok' and what comes next|publisher=[[Zap2it]]|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-19}}</ref><ref name="JOHN HODGMAN: RAGNAROK ON NETFLIX">{{cite web|author=John Hodgman|url=http://www.johnhodgman.com/RAGNAROK|title=JOHN HODGMAN: RAGNAROK ON NETFLIX|publisher=[[Tumblr]]|date=10 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-19}}</ref><ref name="John Hodgman Picks His 5 Favorite TV Thingies of the Year ... From the Future">{{cite web|author=John Hodgman|url=http://www.johnhodgman.com/RAGNAROK|title=John Hodgman Picks His 5 Favorite TV Thingies of the Year ... From the Future|publisher=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]|date=14 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-19}}</ref> The special featured material from Hodgman's most recent book, ''[[That Is All (book)|That Is All]]'', and his [[2012 phenomenon|December 21, 2012]] show at The Bell House in New York.<ref name="John Hodgman on his Netflix comedy special 'Ragnarok' and what comes next" /><ref name="Interview: John Hodgman Talks About John Hodgman: Chicagoist">{{cite web|author=[[Samantha Abernethy]]|url=http://chicagoist.com/2013/06/12/john_hodgman_interview.php|title=Interview: John Hodgman Talks About John Hodgman: Chicagoist|publisher=[[Chicagoist]]|date=12 June 2013|accessdate=2013-06-19}}</ref>

